    {
      "japanese": "もの",
      "reading_romaji": "mono",
      "translation": "thing / stuff / object",
      "casual_usage": "もの turns up constantly in day-to-day speech — 「これ、だれのもの？」(Kore, dare no mono?) is 'Whose thing is this?' and 「いいものみつけた！」(Ii mono mitsuketa!) is the excited 'Found something great!' It's also the backbone of compounds you've already seen: のみもの (drink) and たべもの (food) are both built from もの.",
      "formal_usage": "The word itself doesn't shift register — only the surrounding verb does. A shop clerk returning something says 「こちらはお客様のものでございます」(Kochira wa okyakusama no mono de gozaimasu) with full formality, while もの sits unchanged in the middle.",
