    {
      "japanese": "のほほん",
      "reading_romaji": "nohohon",
      "translation": "blissfully carefree; in a contented daze; pleasantly spaced-out",
      "what_it_is": "のほほん is a gitaigo — a Japanese mimetic word that captures a psychological state no single English word can hold. It describes the serene, slightly dazed feeling of someone who is perfectly content and completely unbothered by the world: a cat napping in a warm patch of sun, a person wandering a market with no agenda, your friend who somehow never seems stressed about anything. It's not laziness — it's the art of peaceful obliviousness.",
      "similar_words": [
